Although fever is an almost universal symptom of malaria, infections with different Plasmodium species may have somewhat variable clinical presentations (Table 1
). Severe malaria is most often due to infection with P falciparum, which can reach higher parasite levels than other species.8
P falciparum accounts for 80% of United States malaria cases seen in child travelers.2 In contrast, P vivax and P ovale infections are rarely fatal but carry the risk of reactivation of dormant liver-stage parasites.9, 10 Chronic asymptomatic bloodstream infection may result from P malariae infection, which can also cause a nephrotic syndrome from immune complex deposition in the kidney.33 Less often seen in travelers, P knowlesi is a zoonotic malaria parasite of long-tailed macaques, increasingly recognized as a cause of severe human infections that may be misdiagnosed as the less harmful P malariae species.34
